 "description": "This large, rustic stone windmill features a stout, cylindrical main body constructed primarily from stone bricks and stripped spruce logs, giving it a medieval aesthetic. The structure measures approximately 17 blocks wide, 19 blocks deep, and 18 blocks high, encompassing two stories. Its base is a mix of red terracotta and gray stone, suggesting a weathered foundation. The windmill is topped with a dark brown, blocky roof, and four prominent white wool sails extend from the upper section, indicating its purpose. The overall color palette is earthy, dominated by the browns of the wood and the grays and reds of the stone, with the stark white of the sails providing a visual contrast. Surrounding the base of the windmill is a small agricultural plot, featuring planted carrots, potatoes, and wheat on farmland, bordered by gravel paths.\n\nThe interior of the windmill, though not fully visible, is designed for functionality across its two stories. The ground floor likely serves as a working area, possibly housing grinding mechanisms, while the upper floor would provide access to the rotating sails and potentially storage or living quarters. The design suggests a single, open room per floor, typical of a rustic working structure. Circulation between the floors would be facilitated by a simple internal staircase. Lighting within the structure would be minimal, relying on small, strategically placed openings or windows, given the solid construction. The overall atmosphere is utilitarian and agrarian, reflecting its role as a key piece of medieval farm infrastructure."
